column595: I looked first at my squares and wanted to go for the highest one. I then looked at the other choices people would make if I were to go for my highest one and I would choose based on other people's choices to my choice and tried to choose options in which we would all benefit. I assumed the others were looking at the different paths to take as well and so I figured I could have a relative idea of who would choose what that could lead to all of us getting our highest value or second highest value.

I thought that people were going to try to get as many points as possible  which makes sense since there's incentive. In that case I focused mostly on what the other color in my box to see what that person's number options were. If they were very clearly going to choose X  for example  I would look at my chart and pick the highest number assuming they would choose X  even if that wasn't the highest number in my chart. I started noticing a trend with that as well  so I kept using it. There were a couple where people had to gamble on the high and low number or two medium numbers  in which case I looked at the other charts and kind of back tracked to see what others would choose  which of course wasn't as successful. Basically  overall  I went for the best number considering other peoples highest numbers and once I caught on to that trend  it seemd to work pretty well.

only one color will have each X nembers larger than the Y numbers  or each Y numbers larger than the X numbers. Then I will assum the person of that color will chose the letter with larger numbers. I will keep guessing this way  until I get to chose my color.

I looked at all the best possible outcomes for everyone as a whole  and sometimes had to give up the best option for     myself because I knew it was a worse option for someone else so they would not choose that option.

Green has the easiest choice because each X row is greater than its Y counterpart. Moving from this choice of XG  Red would pick XR (because 24>6)  meaning that Orange would choose YO  meaning that Blue would pick XB. Each player is trying to maximize their own individual earnings based off of the likely moves of others. In this situation  if Green acts rationally (as in  wants the most tokens possible)  these are the logical choices for the rest of the group.
I just chose the one that is less risky.
I tried to look to see how my choice would affect other squares. If I could choose one row that had the highest numbers I was choosing that one because I would get a large amount.

First I looked for the "decider" team that really only has one option (where the two highest numbers in his/her box were in the same row). From then on  I tracked what the other teams will do based on that choice and I chose accordingly.

So there was always color where one matrix row's pay offs was larger than than the other row's pay offs. They would thus chose that line. Depending on which line I was in  I would calculate which the next person would do all the way until it came to my matrix. I would chose my decision based off of the decisions others should chose. For instance  if for Red's pay off matrix had the top line 30 and 42  and his bottom line was 8 and 10. You know he will chose the top line XR. Thus  I would look to the one matrix where Red's decision will affect the other person's pay off matrix. Let's say its green pay off matrix. The green person will know that red is chosing XR and thus he will chose the best pay off based off the fact that his top column will be XR. I would extrapulate that rationale though all of the matrixs until it reached the matrix that affected me.

Look for the person (color) that has two of his or her highest payoff numbers in the same row (ex: In display 3  Green has 20 and 26 in row XG  the two highest numbers in his 2x2 square). I would make my decisions based on that person  knowing he would pick the row with the two highest numbers because it would make no sense for him to pick the other row (ex: YG). I would then use that information to figure out what other players would pick to decide what I should pick.

I looked at the payoff of the person that I depended on to judge what they were most likely to choose. If their choices were a crapshoot (both their X and Y columns having big and small numbers)  I switched to the person that they relied on until I found one person that had a "guaranteed" pick -- where one of their rows both contained numbers that were higher than the other rows (for example  if the choices were XR were 20 and 25  and the choices for YR were 8 and 10  there's no reason not to choose XR no matter what choices the other players have).  |  | Using this method  I was able to mostly figure out how to maximize my profit by choosing the highest number that had the highest probability of actually being chosen.
after match 4 or 5  I realize that there is always one person that got a absolute advantage in choosing one. So I can use that to guess the choices of all players.
